This code creates a simple HTML page with a sticky header. The `header` element is styled to be sticky and fixed at the top of the viewport using CSS. When you scroll down, the header will remain visible at the top of the screen.

To make the header stick when scrolling, we can use JavaScript as follows:

```javascript
window.addEventListener('scroll', function() {
    var header = document.querySelector('header');
    if (window.scrollY > 0) {
        header.style.position = 'fixed';
        header.style.top = '0';
    } else {
        header.style.position = 'sticky';
        header.style.top = '0';
    }
});
```

This JavaScript code listens for the `scroll` event on the window. When the user scrolls down, it changes the position of the header to fixed and sets its top value to 0. When the user scrolls back up, it changes the position of the header back to sticky and sets its top value to 0.
